\pard\plain\s70\qc\sa120\b\f0\fs24\sl360\slmult1 \fi360 \fs20 Abstract\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl360\slmult1 \li1024\ri1024\fi360 \fs20  {} In this work, the following light weakly bound atomic nuclei are studied: {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}He, {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Li, and {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 9})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be. A three-body model {{\u945*}} + 2N for {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}He and {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Li, and 2{{\u945*}} + N model for {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 9})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be are applied. The wave function of the three-body system is obtained within the framework of the Stochastic Variational Model based on the Gaussian basis. The interaction potentials for three-body systems have a Pauli projector, which excludes forbidden states. An analytical expression is obtained for the density distribution function of nuclear matter using the three-body wave function. The root-mean-square matter radii of {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}He, {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Li, {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 9})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be nuclei are calculated and given comparisons with other sources.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl360\slmult1 \li1024\ri1024\fi360 \fs20 The interactions of {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}He, {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Li, and {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 9})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be with the simplest particles, such as {{\u945*}}, {{\i d}} are studied in detail. On the basis of the calculated density distribution functions, the folding interaction potentials are obtained. The resulting folding interaction potential is applied to calculate the differential cross sections of elastic scattering in the framework of the optical model. Using the Coupled Channels approach for the {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 9})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be induced reactions the role of different reaction channels is studied, and deformation parameters are derived. The comparisons of theoretical cross sections with experimental data in inelastic channels for nuclear reaction {{\i d}} + {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 9})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\u8594*}}}{\fldrslt }}
} {{\i d}} + {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 9})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 *})}}{\fldrslt }}
} are given. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl360\slmult1 \li1024\ri1024\fi360 \fs20 Within the framework of the Coupled Reaction Channels method, the cross sections for nuclear reactions of single-nucleon and cluster transfers are calculated taking into account the internal structure of {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}He, {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Li, and {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 9})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be nuclei. The contributions of the {{\u945*}}-cluster and nucleon involved transfer channels for {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}He, {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 6})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Li, and {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 9})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be are demonstrated. The obtained results based on the proposed theoretical approach reflect the cluster structure of the exploring nuclei.\par
