\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl480\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 {Introduction}\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl480\slmult1 \fi360 Humanity has always been interested in the structure of the Universe - how it works, what it consists of. The understanding and naming of modern objects such as molecules and atoms began in antiquity. The meaning of the word atom, in Greek {{\u945*}{\u964*}{\i o}{\u956*}{\i o}{\u962*}}, is indivisible, or the uncut particle of matter. Modern science has gone much deeper and determined that the atom is actually a complex particle. According to the standard model, the fundamental particles are now six quarks, six leptons and their corresponding anti-particles (for more details, see 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_donoghue2014dynamics \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{donoghue2014dynamics}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_griffiths2020introduction \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{griffiths2020introduction}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_ramond1999journeys \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{ramond1999journeys}}}
]). This has been achieved mainly through theoretical predictions and the development of integrated complex technology, detection systems designed to detect even the smallest particle of fundamental interactions. Particularly, in the modern nuclear physics the experimental techniques have also been successfully developed in the field of the production of secondary beams. Secondary beams, being rare and unstable nuclei, allow studying the properties and characteristics of the dripline nuclei, challenging the nuclear physics.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl480\slmult1 \fi360 In recent years, the study of light weakly bound nuclei has not become less interesting due to the successful development of experimental facilities 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_ter2004radioactive \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{ter2004radioactive}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_yano2007riken \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{yano2007riken}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_gade2016nscl \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{gade2016nscl}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_hong2014plan \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{hong2014plan}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_fukuda2013identification \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{fukuda2013identification}}}
]. It is known that in nuclei the nucleons tend to group into clusters. A well known manifestation of the cluster structure in heavy nuclei is the {{\u945*}}-decay of {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up6({\fs20 238})}}{\fldrslt }}
}U, first experimentally discovered by E. Rutherford 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_rutherford1899viii \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{rutherford1899viii}}}
]. The {{\u945*}}-decay means that {{\u945*}}-cluster can be formed in the uranium nucleus as an individual subsystem with the following emission. The first quantitative theory of {{\u945*}}-decay was developed by G. Gamov (see 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_stuewer1986gamow \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{stuewer1986gamow}}}
]). In addition to {{\u945*}}-decay, there is also a cluster decay, where an emitted particle can be a heavy nucleus, for example \endash  {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up6({\fs20 12})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_poenaru2012cluster \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{poenaru2012cluster}}}
].\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl480\slmult1 \fi360 There are many theoretical approaches 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_descouvemont200112be \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{descouvemont200112be}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_tohsaki2001alpha \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{tohsaki2001alpha}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_kanada1995structure \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{kanada1995structure}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_pudliner1997quantum \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{pudliner1997quantum}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_zhukov1993bound \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{zhukov1993bound}}}
] devoted to studying the structure of exotic nuclei. In particular, the nuclear excitation function for light exotic nuclei is well reproduced by the No Core Shell Model (NCSM) 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_navratil2009recent \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{navratil2009recent}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_forssen2005large \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{forssen2005large}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_navratil2003ab \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{navratil2003ab}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_navratil2002ab \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{navratil2002ab}}}
]. The method uses one-particle basis function of the harmonic oscillator, realistic NN, NNN interactions. This method is reduced to solving the {{\i A}}-nucleon Schr\'f6dinger equation on the basis containing all possible configurations of {{\i A}}-nucleon oscillator functions. However, the size of the basis grows rapidly with the number of nucleons, the reliability of the NCSM model calculations decreases in the case of heavy nuclei. At present, the capabilities of modern computational machines make it possible to calculate with sufficient accuracy for nuclei with masses {{\i A}{\u8804*}16}. For example, in Ref. 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_forssen2005large \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{forssen2005large}}}
] within the framework of this model, the excitation spectrum of the one-particle basis for the {\up8\fs20 9}Beis in good agreement with the experimental data 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_tilley2004energy \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{tilley2004energy}}}
]. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl480\slmult1 \fi360 The microscopic description, that is, taking into account the NN effective potential, of the break-up reaction is presented in the Resonating Group Method (RGM) 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_horiuchi1970generator \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{horiuchi1970generator}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_tang1978resonating \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{tang1978resonating}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_wheeler1937mathematical \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{wheeler1937mathematical}}}
]. Generalization of the RGM consists in constructing overall mathematically equivalent methods for the simultaneous calculation in the nuclear structures and nuclear reactions. The practical application of this method is also limited in the region of the lightest nuclei due to the lack of computational power in the antisymmetrization process. In the work 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_nesterov2010three \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{nesterov2010three}}}
] the algebraic RGM was successfully applied in describing the internal structure {\up8\fs20 6}He, {\up8\fs20 6}Li, and {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up6({\fs20 8})}}{\fldrslt }}
}He nuclei, their rms matter and proton and neutron radii, as well as nuclear matter distribution density were calculated. Also the fusion reactions at low energies with {\up8\fs20 6}Hewere presented.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl480\slmult1 \fi360 Similar to the RGM 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_horiuchi1970generator \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{horiuchi1970generator}}}
], is the Generator Coordinate Method (GCM), if one takes the full model space of the basis Bloch-Brink wave functions 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_brink1966proceedings \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{brink1966proceedings}}}
]. In the framework of the GCM it is possible to carry out calculations for the nuclei with medium masses taking into account a few clusters. For scattering problems, the RGM can be applied rather straightforwardly because the inter-cluster wave function is explicitly treated. On the other hand, in the application of the GCM to scattering problems, it is necessary to connect the basis wave functions in the internal region with continuum states in the asymptotic region at a chosen channel radius 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_descouvemont2010r \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{descouvemont2010r}}}
]. Microscopic three-body calculations for two valence neutrons around a core nucleus have been achieved by many groups to investigate the neutron halo and two-neutron correlation in drip-line nuclei such as {\up8\fs20 6}He{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up6({\fs20 14})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_arai1999structure \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{arai1999structure}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_descouvemont1995halo \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{descouvemont1995halo}}}
]. The {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up6({\fs20 12})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be using the GCM has been studied 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_descouvemont200112be \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{descouvemont200112be}}}
]. In this work a negative-parity band was found, electromagnetic transition probabilities and partial widths of molecular states were calculated.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl480\slmult1 \fi360 In addition to the above theoretical approaches, there is the Stochastic Variational Method (SVM) 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_kukulin1977stochastic \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{kukulin1977stochastic}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_voronchev1994study \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{voronchev1994study}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_kukulin1986detailed \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{kukulin1986detailed}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_kukulin1984detailed \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{kukulin1984detailed}}}
]. The SVM uses the Gaussian function as a basis function, which is convenient for deriving analytically matrix elements of the Hamiltonian. The corresponding Hamiltonian contains a Pauli projector 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_kukulin1978orthogonal \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{kukulin1978orthogonal}}}
], that removes forbidden states. The variational method describes well the internal structures of {\up8\fs20 6}He, {\up8\fs20 6}Li{\up8\fs20 9}Be
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_kukulin1984detailed \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{kukulin1984detailed}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_kukulin1986detailed \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{kukulin1986detailed}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_voronchev1994study \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{voronchev1994study}}}
]. In particular, the electromagnetic properties, geometric parameters and configuration weights are in good agreement with the methods, where they are obtained by exact solutions of three-body problems. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl480\slmult1 \fi360 To describe the elastic scattering in the field of a complex potential, one usually uses the Optical Model (OM), first presented in Ref. 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_feshbach1958optical \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{feshbach1958optical}}}
]. Within the framework of this model, the nucleus is considered as a transparent substance that has the ability to absorb. In practice, this method describes the experimental data well providing the direct information on the nucleus-nucleus interaction potential. However, the ambiguity of the optical potential parameters reduces the merits of optical model. To study the inelastic channels, transfer reactions and their use to describe experimental data the Distorted Wave Born Approximation (DWBA) method has been successfully applied 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_satchler1960gamma \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{satchler1960gamma}}}
]. The DWBA method proved to be appropriate and successful in describing the cross section of nuclear reactions involving the ground and low-lying excited nuclear states of single-particle as well as collective nature. The method becomes inadequate, since the reaction leads to the broad or strongly overlapped final states. In this case the couples channel formalism has to be applied.\par
