}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl480\slmult1 \sb240 \fi360 In light nuclei, the cluster structure can often clearly manifest itself in the dripline region of the nuclear map. These series include such nuclei as {\up8\fs20 6}He, {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up6({\fs20 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Li, {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up6({\fs20 12})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be and other exotic nuclei. However, there are also stable nuclei with apparent cluster structures. These include such nuclei as {\up8\fs20 6}Li, {\up8\fs20 9}Be, {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up6({\fs20 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B and others. Numerous experimental data 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_canto2006fusion \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{canto2006fusion}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_brown2007 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{brown2007}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_papka2007 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{papka2007}}}
] allow us to treat such nuclei as multi-cluster systems, including tightly bound {{\u945*}}-clusters and valence nucleons. A visual representation of how these nuclei can be arranged in the cluster model is illustrated in Fig {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMfig_exotic_nuclei \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{1}}}. For these nuclei the relative motion of internal subsystems determines the property and mechanisms of nuclear reactions. In the figure, we see that the simplest nuclei with a cluster structure are {\up8\fs20 6}He, {\up8\fs20 6}Li, and {\up8\fs20 9}Be. Their structures are ideally suited to consideration within the framework of the three-body model. Moreover, it should be noted that the interaction of pairs inside these nuclei is well known, which can be used in constructing a solution to the Schr\'f6dinger equation. An important factor is also the number of scattering experiments conducted to study the structures of these nuclei. Therefore, the objects for investigation in this work have been taken {\up8\fs20 6}He, {\up8\fs20 6}Li, and {\up8\fs20 9}Be.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl480\slmult1 \fi360 The experimental data of elastic scattering of the {\up8\fs20 6}He+ {{\u945*}} and {\up8\fs20 6}Li+ {{\u945*}} data is available at laboratory energies 151 MeV and 166 MeV 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_ter1998two \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{ter1998two}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_oganessian1999dynamics \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{oganessian1999dynamics}}}
]. This experimental data can be used to show the elastic transfer phenomenon through two-neutron transfer between the two {{\u945*}} core. The main motivation of these studies was to probe the relative importance of the "di-neutron" and "cigar" configurations of the valence neutrons in the {\up8\fs20 6}Hestate. The data show the backward angle rise in cross section. Usually it is considered as an indication of characteristic of elastic transfer. The DWBA analysis using the {\up8\fs20 6}He{\up8\fs20 6}Lifunctions built on hyper-spherical harmonics 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_zhukov1993bound \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{zhukov1993bound}}}
], showed good agreement with the backward angle data. Consequently, it is concluded that the di-neutron configuration dominates the {\up8\fs20 6}Hestate wave function. The more detailed study of the {\up8\fs20 6}He+ {{\u945*}} scattering data has carried out in Ref. 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_khoa2004di \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{khoa2004di}}}
] in the framework of the Coupled Reaction Channels (CRC) method. In this work the spectroscopic information of the di-neutron was obtained, a sequential transfer of the di-neutron was implemented in CRC calculations. It was concluded that the two valence neutrons are transferred mainly simultaneously, the rising of cross section at backward angles comes due to the elastic transfer of the {2{\i n}} system. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl480\slmult1 \fi360 Based on the Borromean structure of {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {}\\s\\up6({\fs20 9})}}{\fldrslt }}
}Be, special attention was paid to the breakup processes resulting from the {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {}\\s\\up6({\fs20 9})}}{\fldrslt }}
